---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="About — Daniel Palmer"
  description="CIS grad, three years of RPA at Fastenal, now an AI Analyst at Meraki Private Equity."
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-(--color-text-dim) mb-4">
      About
    </p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] leading-tight">
      I help businesses get their hours back.
    </h1>

    <div class="prose-case mt-12">
      <p>
        I'm Daniel Palmer. I grew up in Minnesota, studied Computer
        Information Systems at <strong>Winona State</strong> (graduated December
        2023), and spent the next three years on a 7-person RPA team at
        Fastenal building automations against SAP, web apps, and internal
        tooling. Together we shipped 100+ automations and the team saved north
        of $30M.
      </p>

      <p>
        In April 2026 I moved to <strong>Meraki Private Equity</strong> as an
        AI Analyst, embedding Claude into <a href="https://gradientfinancial.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Gradient
        Financial Group</a> workflows.
      </p>

      <h2>The frame</h2>
      <p>
        Three years of rules-based RPA taught me that the bottleneck of
        automation is rarely the part that runs — it's the part that <em>decides</em>.
        Rules-based bots are great at filling in 200 fields a minute and
        terrible at telling you whether the invoice that just landed is the
        same vendor as last quarter under a slightly different name.
      </p>
      <p>
        Putting a model in the loop changes the unit of work, not the
        discipline. The same things that made RPA work — sturdy logging,
        deterministic side effects, audit trails — still apply. You just get
        to spend less of your time writing rules for the long tail.
      </p>
      <p>That's the throughline of this site: <strong>automate the workflow, not the UI; automate the judgment, not the rule.</strong></p>

      <h2>Earlier</h2>
      <p>
        Before Fastenal I did the usual CS stations of the cross: a couple of
        internships, a handful of side projects in Python and TypeScript,
        too many half-finished games. The two things from that period that
        still shape how I work are (1) the value of a notebook you actually
        go back to, and (2) the realization that "I'll just script it"
        scales much further than I expected.
      </p>

      <h2>Outside of work</h2>
      <p>
        I live in Shoreview, MN. I read a lot. I keep
        <a href="https://studywheel.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">a small public app</a>
        running for fun. If you'd like to talk shop or just say hi, <a href="/contact">the contact page</a>
        is the easiest way.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
